Organization Overview


Sakhi for South Asian Survivors exists to represent the South Asian and Indo-Caribbean diaspora living in America in a survivor-led movement for gender-justice by providing culturally competent direct services such as a helpline, counseling, advocacy, housing assistance, economic empowerment, food justice, elder abuse intervention, and youth programs that honor the collective and inherent power of all survivors of violence.


Our office offers a unique work environment that is collaborative, fun, and committed to social justice. Sakhi is an equal opportunity employer. Candidates of diverse backgrounds, identities, and abilities are encouraged to apply. For more information on Sakhi, please visit our website at www.sakhi.org.


The Executive Assistant will primarily be responsible for ensuring that the Executive Director’s time and resources are managed as necessary for them to achieve Sakhi’s mission such that it reaches diverse and relevant audiences in the movement for gender justice in the South Asian and Indo-Caribbean diaspora.


This position will report to the Executive Director and, at times, would need to work closely with the Leadership Team, Programs Teams, Communications and Development, Finance and Operations Team to help achieve the organizational goals. A successful candidate should possess great organizational skills and the ability to adapt to situations as they arise.


The daily responsibilities of the Executive Assistant include management of the Executive Director’s calendar with respect to liaising with the Board of Directors and coordinating meetings with benefactors, friends of the organization, federal and local government offices, and other partner organizations or individuals. This role also assists the Executive Director and others on the Leadership Team to organize team and organizational events such as retreats, training and fundraising events. In addition, this role will often serve as the representative for the ED, since they are liasoning on the ED’s behalf.


Sakhi, the nation’s second-oldest South Asian gender justice organization, has pioneered culturally specific approaches to working with survivors of gender-based violence from the South Asian diaspora, and has a 35-year history as a leader in the gender-justice movement.


\\*Please note: Candidates must have a strong commitment to working from an intersectional, anti-racist, and inclusive lens. Those with a background in social justice work are encouraged to apply\\*

**This position is set for a start date of October 1, 2024.**



Position Responsibilities:

* Manage the Executive Director's calendar and appointments, ensuring that all engagements are well-coordinated and timely.
* Coordinate and oversee any travel that the Executive Director might need to undertake, including but not limited to working with host and partner organizations and making travel and stay arrangements.
* Act as a liaison with external partners, including donors, sponsors, media, and community leaders.
* Manage and maintain the organization's filing system, databases, and other administrative tools as needed.
* Attend meetings with ED and compile notes or attend on behalf if unavailable
* Draft and review communications on behalf of ED
* Assist in organizing, executing and managing special events, campaigns, and fundraising activities.
* Organize and coordinate funder site visits to the office.
* Assist in organizing, coordinating and managing team events such as meetings and retreats.
* Work with the Board of Directors to set up quarterly board meetings and any other related tasks.
* Perform other related duties as directed
* Handle sensitive and confidential information with discretion and professionalism.


Desired Skills and Experience:

* V**alues-aligned with Sakhi’s core principles**and mission of eradicating gender-based violence;
* Invested in gender justice, systemic change, and commitment to critiquing and building a movement;
* Be able to practice cultural sensitivity and trauma informed communication
* Two (2) years minimum experience in working as an Executive Assistant, Administrative or Logistics role. Preferably in a non profit setting;
* Willingness to adopt and adapt to an organizational voice;
* Strong interpersonal and collaborative skills;
* Works well across teams;
* Strong attention to detail;
* Displays a positive attitude, shows concern for people and the community, and demonstrates presence, self-confidence, common sense, and good listening ability;
* A “self-starter” and goal-driven to initiate donor visits and fundraising calls;
* Has the desire build external relationships;
* Organized and exhibits “follow-through” on tasks and goals;
* Works well under pressure and juggles multiple time-sensitive tasks skillfully- adheres to deadlines;
* Fluency in South Asian languages, especially Hindi, Urdu, and/or Bengali, is a plus (not required);
* U.S. work authorization required.


This is a part-time role with an expected weekly schedule of 20 hours a week at $25 per hour. Hours can occasionally increase depending on the urgency of work. Sakhi’s office hours are Monday–Friday, 10 AM–6 PM. Staff members have the flexibility to organize their hours over the week. This position can be done fully remote or in person as preferred by the candidate. It is also preferred, but not mandatory, that the Executive Assistant be available Monday–Friday mornings. Some evenings and weekends will be required.



Application Information:
All interested applicants should apply before May 24th, 2024 with an ideal start date of June 15th, 2024.

OUR VISION
To continue as an eminent healthcare provider on Long Island, dedicating ourselves to providing exceptional health care for all our patients and to transform both the lives of the individual, and the community, for the better, one person at a time.



OUR MISSION


To provide access to equitable, optimal healthcare by improving the overall wellness of all individuals in our communities and delivering high quality comprehensive patient centered care.



OUR VALUE PROPOSITION


To provide whole person care that will ensure that all patients have access to primary, specialty and social health care to achieve and maintain optimal wellness at a transparent and affordable cost.



The Harmony Healthcare Long Island, formerly known as (Long Island Federally Qualified Health Center or LIFQHC) is a non-profit healthcare organization with 7 health centers, providing primary care and preventative medicine in the following locations in Nassau County: Roosevelt, Elmont, Hempstead, Freeport, Oceanside, and New Cassel/Westbury. In addition, the Harmony Healthcare Long Island has 3 school-based health centers, WIC offices (Special Supplemental Nutrition Program for Women, Infants, and Children) in 3 locations, and a Health Home Care Coordination program. As federally qualified health centers, we serve the individuals in our communities, providing enhanced services, expanded hours and reduced prescription pricing, while raising the level of care. We treat patients regardless of income, residency or immigration status.



The Harmony Healthcare Long Island offers a stable employment opportunity with a growing company, and competitive base compensation along with health and dental insurance, paid time off, 401-K with company match, paid holidays, employee discounts and much more.



JOB TITLE: Nurse Practitioner


The following statements reflect the general duties, responsibilities and competencies considered necessary to perform the essential functions of the job and should not be considered as a detailed description of all the work requirements of this position.



RESPONSIBILITIES:

* Involved with direct patient physical assessment, education, and health planning;
* Assists in the coordination of services with other disciplines and patient’s insurance plans;
* Advocates for patient in arrangement of medically necessary services;
* Communicates with community’s resources to ascertain adequate assistance for patients in need;
* Refers patients to specialty services when necessary;
* Consults with collaborating physician and other members of the health care team to establish plan of care;
* Participate in LEAN and other activities necessary to implement the multi-disciplinary patient-centered medical home approach for the care of pediatric patients
* Maintains continuity of care by regular patient follow-up;
* Participates in quality assurance process to assure optimal care delivery;
* Provides comprehensive case management services that include emphasis on health promotion and disease prevention;
* Monitors patient outcome in accordance to the practice protocols;
* Collaborates with staff nurses and nursing administrators with assessment and clinical decision in patient care planning;
* Acts as a resource person for the nursing staff;
* Conducts education in service on practice issues;
* Other duties as assigned.



QUALIFICATIONS:

* Minimum 1 year experience as NP
* Graduated from approved Nurse Practitioner Program;
* Licensed as Nurse Practitioner in New York State;
* Basic CPR (BCLS) certification required;
* Specialty Certification Preferred;
* Bilingual in English and Spanish or Creole preferred.



